  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention for the child_process module through input validation at both JavaScript and C++ layers.\n\n## Validation Functions\n\nThe primary JavaScript validation mechanism is implemented in lib/child_process.js:\n\n**validateArgumentNullCheck()** (lib/child_process.js:963-967) validates individual string arguments by checking if they contain null bytes (\\u0000). It throws ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if a null byte is found: 'must be a string without null bytes'.\n\n**validateArgumentsNullCheck()** (lib/child_process.js:970-974) iterates through arrays of arguments (like command arguments or execArgv) and calls validateArgumentNullCheck() on each element to prevent null byte injection in argument arrays.\n\n## Normalization Functions\n\nThree key normalization functions enforce validation across the API:\n\n**normalizeSpawnArguments()** (lib/child_process.js:538-709) normalizes and validates spawn arguments. It:\n- Validates the 'file' parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 540)\n- Validates 'args' array with validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 556)\n- Validates argv0 with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 597)\n- Validates options.shell with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 613)\n- Validates environment variable keys and values with validateArgumentNullCheck() (lines 691-692)\n\n**normalizeExecArgs()** (lib/child_process.js:188-206) validates the command string parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 190), preventing null byte injection in shell commands.\n\n**normalizeExecFileArgs()** (lib/child_process.js:262-296) validates argv0 with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 292) to prevent null byte injection in custom process names.\n\n## Public API Entry Points\n\nAll six main child_process methods use these validation functions:\n\n**exec()** (lib/child_process.js:231-236) calls normalizeExecArgs() which validates the command string against null bytes.\n\n**execSync()** (lib/child_process.js:945-960) uses normalizeExecArgs() for validation before synchronous execution.\n\n**execFile()** (lib/child_process.js:323-522) calls normalizeExecFileArgs() to validate file and argv0 parameters, then calls spawn().\n\n**execFileSync()** (lib/child_process.js:907-924) calls normalizeExecFileArgs() for validation before synchronous execution.\n\n**spawn()** (lib/child_process.js:745-791) calls normalizeSpawnArguments() which performs comprehensive validation of all parameters (file, args, argv0, shell, env) for null bytes.\n\n**spawnSync()** (lib/child_process.js:823-869) calls normalizeSpawnArguments() to validate all parameters before synchronous process spawning.\n\n**fork()** (lib/child_process.js:122-172) validates execPath with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 142) and execArgv with validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 146) to prevent null byte injection in forked processes.\n\n## JavaScript to C++ Interface\n\n**ChildProcess** (lib/internal/child_process.js:254-311) is the JavaScript class that wraps the native Process handle. It:\n- Creates a native Process object via internalBinding('process_wrap') (line 44 imports Process, line 266 creates the handle)\n- Implements ChildProcess.prototype.spawn() (line 354+) which invokes the native spawn method\n- Calls this._handle.spawn(options) (line 395) to pass validated options to C++\n\n## C++ Native Binding\n\n**ProcessWrap** (src/process_wrap.cc:51-346) is the C++ class that implements native process management:\n- Inherits from HandleWrap and provides the native Process binding\n- Exports Initialize() (line 53-69) which sets up the Process constructor and methods\n- Implements Spawn() (line 153-310) which:\n  - Receives already-validated options from JavaScript\n  - Extracts file path, arguments, environment, and stdio configuration\n  - Calls uv_spawn() (line 286) to perform actual OS process spawning\n  - Returns error codes to JavaScript layer\n\nThe validation happens entirely at the JavaScript layer before reaching C++, providing defense-in-depth protection.\n\n## Comprehensive Test Coverage\n\ntest/parallel/test-child-process-reject-null-bytes.js (295 lines) provides regression tests for null byte validation covering:\n- Command string validation (exec, execSync) lines 19-37\n- File path validation (spawn, execFile, execFileSync, spawnSync, fork) lines 40-71\n- Arguments array validation (execFile, execFileSync, fork, spawn, spawnSync) lines 78-101\n- Current working directory validation (lines 104-138)\n- argv0 parameter validation (lines 140-175)\n- Shell parameter validation (lines 177-210)\n- Environment variable keys and values validation (lines 212-282)\n- execPath and execArgv validation for fork (lines 284-294)\n\nAll tests verify that ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE TypeError is thrown when null bytes are detected, preventing command injection attacks via string concatenation or argument manipulation."
}
