  "text": "Node.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention for the child_process module through input validation at both JavaScript and C++ layers.\n\n## Validation Functions\n\nThe primary JavaScript validation mechanism is implemented in lib/child_process.js:\n\n**validateArgumentNullCheck()** (lib/child_process.js:963-967) validates individual string arguments by checking if they contain null bytes (\\u0000). It throws ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE if a null byte is found: 'must be a string without null bytes'.\n\n**validateArgumentsNullCheck()** (lib/child_process.js:970-974) iterates through arrays of arguments (like command arguments or execArgv) and calls validateArgumentNullCheck() on each element to prevent null byte injection in argument arrays.\n\n## Normalization Functions\n\nThree key normalization functions enforce validation across the API:\n\n**normalizeSpawnArguments()** (lib/child_process.js:538-709) normalizes and validates spawn arguments. It:\n- Validates the 'file' parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 540)\n- Validates 'args' array with validateArgumentsNullCheck() (line 556)\n- Validates argv0 with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 597)\n- Validates options.shell with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 613)\n- Validates environment variable keys and values with validateArgumentNullCheck() (lines 691-692)\n\n**normalizeExecArgs()** (lib/child_process.js:188-206) validates the command string parameter with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 190), preventing null byte injection in shell commands.\n\n**normalizeExecFileArgs()** (lib/child_process.js:262-296) validates argv0 with validateArgumentNullCheck() (line 292) to prevent null byte injection in custom process names.\n\n## Public API Entry Points\n\nAll six main child_process methods use these validation functions:\n\n**exec()** (lib/child_process.js:231-236) calls normalizeExecArgs() which validates the command string against null bytes.\n\n**execSync()** (lib/child_process.j